INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("458", "1", "2017-06-13 23:55:39", "2017-06-13 23:55:39", "<img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-227\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Butterfly-pic-1-300x170.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"170\" />\r\n\r\nMy health journey began about 12 years ago after multiple surgeries, debilitating pain &amp; consuming a very sad diet (standard American diet). I was working, living &amp; eating like most people, too much work, not much balance &amp; consuming processed food. At rock bottom &amp; determined to get better, a visit to Mayo Clinic ignited the change. I credit the clinicians for helping me with integrative &amp; holistic options. Those recommendations have forever changed my life both personally &amp; professionally.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-457\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/images-300x266.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"266\" />\r\n\r\nI left a career in the pharmaceutical &amp; med device industry, started educating myself on how to eat (because I had no clue) &amp; pursued a Master’s degree in nutrition. I was excited to be accepted into a new graduate nutrition program at the National University of Natural Medicine in Portland, OR. There were so many advantages to learning in this environment surrounded by research, naturopathic &amp; oriental medicine students. Then there’s the Portland factor that is ridiculously awesome in so many ways! From access to daily farmer’s markets, to sustainability &amp; environmental consciousness, along with plenty of dairy, soy, nut &amp; gluten-free, non-GMO restaurants &amp; food trucks.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-226\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Blog-Page-Pic-Nutrition-300x235.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"235\" />\r\n\r\nI left a career in the pharmaceutical &amp; med device industry, started educating myself on how to eat (because I had no clue) &amp; pursued a Master’s degree in nutrition. I was excited to be accepted into a new graduate nutrition program at the National University of Natural Medicine in Portland, OR. There were so many advantages to learning in this environment surrounded by research, naturopathic &amp; oriental medicine students. Then there’s the Portland factor that is ridiculously awesome in so many ways! From access to daily farmer’s markets, to sustainability &amp; environmental consciousness, along with plenty of dairy, soy, nut &amp; gluten-free, non-GMO restaurants &amp; food trucks.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-358\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screen-Shot-2017-06-05-at-23.47.49-300x209.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"209\" />\r\n\r\nI’m a Nutritionist &amp; Whole Food Nut that wants to help others overcome the hurdles to eating healthy. Thru educational videos, nutrition tips &amp; the Facebook page, I’ll share the health benefits of preparing &amp; eating whole foods. People are overwhelmed with the mass amount of conflicting &amp; rapidly changing nutrition data. I want to simplify &amp; break down the challenges to healthy eating as well as provide wellness &amp; nutrition tips to incorporate into your daily life. I’m not a fan of fad diets that promote one way of eating over another because every person has different nutritive needs that are based upon their biochemical individuality. Healthy eating is a balance of moderation &amp; variation not deprivation. There’s so many foods to discover, eat &amp; enjoy!\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-333\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/cropped-Picture1-1-300x153.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"153\" />\r\n\r\nWhere do I begin? What should I eat? What the heck is a whole food? After hearing these questions asked over &amp; over, I reflected on my food journey &amp; realized the need for food education. We are not taught in school one of the most important things in life; what &amp; how to eat. It’s not pretty when I reflect on my initial attempts at cooking &amp; learning what to eat. Lesson #1 This doesn’t happen overnight. Be patient, have a good sense of humor &amp; embrace your kitchen as a science experiment! Lesson #2 Do not start with fancy recipes because that will only add to the frustration.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-456\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/spices-1914130_1280-268x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"268\" height=\"300\" />\r\n\r\nWhere do I begin? What should I eat? What the heck is a whole food? After hearing these questions asked over &amp; over, I reflected on my food journey &amp; realized the need for food education. We are not taught in school one of the most important things in life; what &amp; how to eat. It’s not pretty when I reflect on my initial attempts at cooking &amp; learning what to eat. Lesson #1 This doesn’t happen overnight. Be patient, have a good sense of humor &amp; embrace your kitchen as a science experiment! Lesson #2 Do not start with fancy recipes because that will only add to the frustration.", "About", "My health journey began about 12 years ago after multiple surgeries, debilitating pain &amp; consuming a very sad diet (standard american diet). I was working, living &amp; eating like most people....too much work, not much balance &amp; consuming processed food. At rock bottom &amp; determined to get better, a visit to Mayo Clinic ignited the change. I credit the physcians for helping me get started in a new direction by discussing integrative &amp; holistic options. Those recommendations have forever changed my life both personally &amp; professionally.", "inherit", "closed", "closed", "", "6-revision-v1", "", "", "2017-06-13 23:55:39", "2017-06-13 23:55:39", "", "6", "http://localhost:8888/food-nut/2017/