" align=\"left\" vspace=\"”50”/\" />\r\n\r\nSo, this Whole Food Nut went from consuming nothing but diet-coke, Doritos &amp; iceberg lettuce to cooking &amp; preparing all my meals. If it had no nutritional value, I ate it. I literally didn’t know how to boil an egg (no joke). Now I’m a crazy nut in the kitchen who loves to experiment with new foods &amp; recipes while dancing to tunes. It’s an endless science project.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h1></h1>\r\n<h3>Whole Food Nut Tips</h3>\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-358 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screen-Shot-2017-06-05-at-23.47.49-300x209.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"209\" align=\"left\" />\r\n\r\nI’m a Nutritionist &amp; Whole Food Nut that wants to help others overcome the hurdles to eating healthy. Thru educational videos, nutrition tips &amp; the Facebook page, I’ll share the health benefits of preparing &amp; eating whole foods. People are overwhelmed with the mass amount of conflicting &amp; rapidly changing nutrition data. I want to simplify &amp; break down the challenges to healthy eating as well as provide wellness &amp; nutrition tips to incorporate into your daily life. I’m not a fan of fad diets that promote one way of eating over another because every person has different nutritive needs that are based upon their biochemical individuality. Healthy eating is a balance of moderation &amp; variation not deprivation. There’s so many foods to discover, eat &amp; enjoy!\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-333 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/cropped-Picture1-1-300x153.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"153\" align=\"left\" />\r\n\r\nWhere do I begin? What should I eat? What the heck is a whole food? After hearing these questions asked over &amp; over, I reflected on my food journey &amp; realized the need for food education. We are not taught in school one of the most important things in life; what &amp; how to eat. It’s not pretty when I reflect on my initial attempts at cooking &amp; learning what to eat. Lesson #1 This doesn’t happen overnight. Be patient, have a good sense of humor &amp; embrace your kitchen as a science experiment! Lesson #2 Do not start with fancy recipes because that will only add to the frustration.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-456 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/spices-1914130_1280-268x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"268\" height=\"300\" align=\"left\" />\r\n\r\nLesson #3 Once you start to notice the benefits from eating healthy, you’ll wish you did it sooner. What motivates you? Remind yourself of that every day! If you have the desire to change, it’s never too late. Once you learn the basics, practice &amp; get comfortable in the kitchen, you won’t need to rely as much on following recipes by the book. You just need to start, experiment &amp; keep going because it’ll be worth it! We’ll explore cooking basics, preparing meals with whole foods, nutrient dense foods, ‘supplementing’ with food, grocery shopping, food labels, mindful eating and gardening.", "About", "My health journey began about 12 years ago after multiple surgeries, debilitating pain &amp; consuming a very sad diet (standard american diet). I was working, living &amp; eating like most people....too much work, not much balance &amp; consuming processed food. At rock bottom &amp; determined to get better, a visit to Mayo Clinic ignited the change. I credit the physcians for helping me get started in a new direction by discussing integrative &amp; holistic options. Those recommendations have forever changed my life both personally &amp; professionally.", "inherit", "closed", "closed", "", "6-revision-v1", "", "", "2017-06-14 00:04:10", "2017-06-14 00:04:10", "", "6", "http://localhost:8888/food-nut/2017/06/14/6-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("465", "1", "2017-06-14 00:05:38", "2017-06-14 00:05:38", "<h3>Whole Food Nut Story</h3>\r\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-227 \" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Butterfly-pic-1-300x170.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"294\" height=\"167\" align=\"left\" vspace=\"”50”\" />\r\n\r\n<p align=\"justify\">My health journey began about 12 years ago after multiple surgeries, debilitating pain &amp; consuming a very sad diet (standard American diet). I was working, living &amp; eating like most people, too much work, not much balance &amp; consuming processed food. At rock bottom &amp; determined to get better, a visit to Mayo Clinic ignited the change. I credit the clinicians for helping me with integrative &amp; holistic options. Those recommendations have forever changed my life both personally &amp; professionally.</p>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"wp-image-457 size-medium alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/images-300x266.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"266\" align=\"left\" vspace=\"”50”\" />\r\n\r\n<p align=\"justify\">I left a career in the pharmaceutical &amp; med device industry, started educating myself on how to eat (because I had no clue) &amp; pursued a Master’s degree in nutrition. I was excited to be accepted into a new graduate nutrition program at the National University of Natural Medicine in Portland, OR. There were so many advantages to learning in this environment surrounded by research, naturopathic &amp; oriental medicine students. Then there’s the Portland factor that is ridiculously awesome in so many ways! From access to daily farmer’s markets, to sustainability &amp; environmental consciousness, along with plenty of dairy, soy, nut &amp; gluten-free, non-GMO restaurants &amp; food trucks.</p>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-226 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Blog-Page-Pic-Nutrition-300x235.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"235\" align=\"left\" vspace=\"”50”/\" />\r\n\r\n<p align=\"justify\">So, this Whole Food Nut went from consuming nothing but diet-coke, Doritos &amp; iceberg lettuce to cooking &amp; preparing all my meals. If it had no nutritional value, I ate it. I literally didn’t know how to boil an egg (no joke). Now I’m a crazy nut in the kitchen who loves to experiment with new foods &amp; recipes while dancing to tunes. It’s an endless science project.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Whole Food Nut Tips</h3>\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-358 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screen-Shot-2017-06-05-at-23.47.49-300x209.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"209\" align=\"left\" />\r\n\r\n<p align=\"justify\">I’m a Nutritionist &amp; Whole Food Nut that wants to help others overcome the hurdles to eating healthy. Thru educational videos, nutrition tips &amp; the Facebook page, I’ll share the health benefits of preparing &amp; eating whole foods. People are overwhelmed with the mass amount of conflicting &amp; rapidly changing nutrition data. I want to simplify &amp; break down the challenges to healthy eating as well as provide wellness &amp; nutrition tips to incorporate into your daily life. I’m not a fan of fad diets that promote one way of eating over another because every person has different nutritive needs that are based upon their biochemical individuality. Healthy eating is a balance of moderation &amp; variation not deprivation. There’s so many foods to discover, eat &amp; enjoy!</p>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-333 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/cropped-Picture1-1-300x153.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"153\" align=\"left\" />\r\n\r\n<p align=\"justify\">Where do I begin? What should I eat? What the heck is a whole food? After hearing these questions asked over &amp; over, I reflected on my food journey &amp; realized the need for food education. We are not taught in school one of the most important things in life; what &amp; how to eat. It’s not pretty when I reflect on my initial attempts at cooking &amp; learning what to eat. Lesson #1 This doesn’t happen overnight. Be patient, have a good sense of humor &amp; embrace your kitchen as a science experiment! Lesson #2 Do not start with fancy recipes because that will only add to the frustration.</p>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-456 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/spices-1914130_1280-268x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"268\" height=\"300\" align=\"left\" />\r\n\r\n<p align=\"justify\">Lesson #3 Once you start to notice the benefits from eating healthy, you’ll wish you did it sooner. What motivates you? Remind yourself of that every day! If you have the desire to change, it’s never too late. Once you learn the basics, practice &amp; get comfortable in the kitchen, you won’t need to rely as much on following recipes by the book. You just need to start, experiment &amp; keep going because it’ll be worth it! We’ll explore cooking basics, preparing meals with whole foods, nutrient dense foods, ‘supplementing’ with food, grocery shopping, food labels, mindful eating and gardening.</p>", "About", "My health journey began about 12 years ago after multiple surgeries, debilitating pain &amp; consuming a very sad diet (standard american diet). I was working, living &amp; eating like most people....too much work, not much balance &amp; consuming processed food. At rock bottom &amp; determined to get better, a visit to Mayo Clinic ignited the change. I credit the physcians for helping me get started in a new direction by discussing integrative &amp; holistic options. Those recommendations have forever changed my life both personally &amp; professionally.", "inherit", "closed", "closed", "", "6-revision-v1", "", "", "2017-06-14 00:05:38", "2017-06-14 00:05:38", "", "6", "http://localhost:8888/food-nut/2017/06/14/6-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("466", "1", "2017-06-14 00:06:04", "2017-06-14 00:06:04", "<h3>Whole Food Nut Story</h3>\r\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-227 \" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Butterfly-pic-1-300x170.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"294\" height=\"167\" align=\"left\" vspace=\"”50”\" />\r\n<p align=\"justify\">My health journey began about 12 years ago after multiple surgeries, debilitating pain &amp; consuming a very sad diet (standard American diet). I was working, living &amp; eating like most people, too much work, not much balance &amp; consuming processed food. At rock bottom &amp; determined to get better, a visit to Mayo Clinic ignited the change. I credit the clinicians for helping me with integrative &amp; holistic options. Those recommendations have forever changed my life both personally &amp; professionally.</p>\r\n<img class=\"wp-image-457 size-medium alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/images-300x266.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"266\" align=\"left\" vspace=\"”50”\" />\r\n<p align=\"justify\">I left a career in the pharmaceutical &amp; med device industry, started educating myself on how to eat (because I had no clue) &amp; pursued a Master’s degree in nutrition. I was excited to be accepted into a new graduate nutrition program at the National University of Natural Medicine in Portland, OR. There were so many advantages to learning in this environment surrounded by research, naturopathic &amp; oriental medicine students. Then there’s the Portland factor that is ridiculously awesome in so many ways! From access to daily farmer’s markets, to sustainability &amp; environmental consciousness, along with plenty of dairy, soy, nut &amp; gluten-free, non-GMO restaurants &amp; food trucks.</p>\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-226 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Blog-Page-Pic-Nutrition-300x235.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"235\" align=\"left\" vspace=\"”50”/\" />\r\n<p align=\"justify\">So, this Whole Food Nut went from consuming nothing but diet-coke, Doritos &amp; iceberg lettuce to cooking &amp; preparing all my meals. If it had no nutritional value, I ate it. I literally didn’t know how to boil an egg (no joke). Now I’m a crazy nut in the kitchen who loves to experiment with new foods &amp; recipes while dancing to tunes. It’s an endless science project.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n<h3>Whole Food Nut Tips</h3>\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-358 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Screen-Shot-2017-06-05-at-23.47.49-300x209.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"209\" align=\"left\" />\r\n<p align=\"justify\">I’m a Nutritionist &amp; Whole Food Nut that wants to help others overcome the hurdles to eating healthy. Thru educational videos, nutrition tips &amp; the Facebook page, I’ll share the health benefits of preparing &amp; eating whole foods. People are overwhelmed with the mass amount of conflicting &amp; rapidly changing nutrition data. I want to simplify &amp; break down the challenges to healthy eating as well as provide wellness &amp; nutrition tips to incorporate into your daily life. I’m not a fan of fad diets that promote one way of eating over another because every person has different nutritive needs that are based upon their biochemical individuality. Healthy eating is a balance of moderation &amp; variation not deprivation. There’s so many foods to discover, eat &amp; enjoy!</p>\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-333 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/cropped-Picture1-1-300x153.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"153\" align=\"left\" />\r\n<p align=\"justify\">Where do I begin? What should I eat? What the heck is a whole food? After hearing these questions asked over &amp; over, I reflected on my food journey &amp; realized the need for food education. We are not taught in school one of the most important things in life; what &amp; how to eat. It’s not pretty when I reflect on my initial attempts at cooking &amp; learning what to eat. Lesson #1 This doesn’t happen overnight. Be patient, have a good sense of humor &amp; embrace your kitchen as a science experiment! Lesson #2 Do not start with fancy recipes because that will only add to the frustration.</p>\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-456 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/spices-1914130_1280-268x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"268\" height=\"300\" align=\"left\" />\r\n<p align=\"justify\">Lesson #3 Once you start to notice the benefits from eating healthy, you’ll wish you did it sooner. What motivates you? Remind yourself of that every day! If you have the desire to change, it’s never too late. Once you learn the basics, practice &amp; get comfortable in the kitchen, you won’t need to rely as much on following recipes by the book. You just need to start, experiment &amp; keep going because it’ll be worth it! We’ll explore cooking basics, preparing meals with whole foods, nutrient dense foods, ‘supplementing’ with food, grocery shopping, food labels, mindful eating and gardening.</p>", "About", "My health journey began about 12 years ago after multiple surgeries, debilitating pain &amp; consuming a very sad diet (standard american diet). I was working, living &amp; eating like most people....too much work, not much balance &amp; consuming processed food. At rock bottom &amp; determined to get better, a visit to Mayo Clinic ignited the change. I credit the physcians for helping me get started in a new direction by discussing integrative &amp; holistic options. Those recommendations have forever changed my life both personally &amp; professionally.", "inherit", "closed", "closed", "", "6-revision-v1", "", "", "2017-06-14 00:06:04", "2017-06-14 00:06:04", "", "6", "http://localhost:8888/food-nut/2017/06/14/6-revision-v1/", "0", "re