; what &amp; how to eat. It’s not pretty when I reflect on my initial attempts at cooking &amp; learning what to eat. Lesson #1 This doesn’t happen overnight. Be patient, have a good sense of humor &amp; embrace your kitchen as a science experiment! Lesson #2 Do not start with fancy recipes because that will only add to the frustration.</p>\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-475 alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/spices-1914130_1280-768x861-1-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" />\r\n<p align=\"justify\">Lesson #3 Once you start to notice the benefits from eating healthy, you’ll wish you did it sooner. What motivates you? Remind yourself of that every day! If you have the desire to change, it’s never too late. Once you learn the basics, practice &amp; get comfortable in the kitchen, you won’t need to rely as much on following recipes by the book. You just need to start, experiment &amp; keep going because it’ll be worth it! We’ll explore cooking basics, preparing meals with whole foods, nutrient dense foods, ‘supplementing’ with food, grocery shopping, food labels, mindful eating and gardening.</p>", "About", "My health journey began about 12 years ago after multiple surgeries, debilitating pain &amp; consuming a very sad diet (standard american diet). I was working, living &amp; eating like most people....too much work, not much balance &amp; consuming processed food. At rock bottom &amp; determined to get better, a visit to Mayo Clinic ignited the change. I credit the physcians for helping me get started in a new direction by discussing integrative &amp; holistic options. Those recommendations have forever changed my life both personally &amp; professionally.", "inherit", "closed", "closed", "", "6-revision-v1", "", "", "2017-06-14 00:38:52", "2017-06-14 00:38:52", "", "6", "http://localhost:8888/food-nut/2017/06/14/6-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
