lected on my food journey &amp; realized the need for food education. We are not taught in school one of the most important things in life; what &amp; how to eat. It’s not pretty when I reflect on my initial attempts at cooking &amp; learning what to eat. Lesson #1 This doesn’t happen overnight. Be patient, have a good sense of humor &amp; embrace your kitchen as a science experiment! Lesson #2 Do not start with fancy recipes because that will only add to the frustration. Lesson #3 Once you start to notice the benefits from eating healthy, you’ll wish you did it sooner.</p>\r\n<img class=\"wp-image-591 size-medium alignleft\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/food-nut/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/pexels-photo-196643-300x200.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"justify\">What motivates you? Remind yourself of that every day! If you have the desire to change, it’s never too late. Once you learn the basics, practice &amp; get comfortable in the kitchen, you won’t need to rely as much on following recipes by the book. You just need to start, experiment &amp; keep going because it’ll be worth it! We’ll explore cooking basics, preparing meals with whole foods, nutrient dense foods, ‘supplementing’ with food, grocery shopping, food labels, mindful eating and gardening.</p>", "About", "My health journey began about 12 years ago after multiple surgeries, debilitating pain &amp; consuming a very sad diet (standard american diet). I was working, living &amp; eating like most people....too much work, not much balance &amp; consuming processed food. At rock bottom &amp; determined to get better, a visit to Mayo Clinic ignited the change. I credit the physcians for helping me get started in a new direction by discussing integrative &amp; holistic options. Those recommendations have forever changed my life both personally &amp; professionally.", "inherit", "closed", "closed", "", "6-revision-v1", "", "", "2017-07-11 23:33:35", "2017-07-